          "body": "The chapter's most chilling verdict comes in three verses centered on the verb *metaschēmatizō* (to refashion outwardly, three times in three verses). The false apostles 'disguise themselves as apostles of Christ' — and this is unsurprising because 'Satan himself disguises himself as an angel of light,' so it is no marvel that his servants disguise themselves as 'servants of righteousness.' The theological claim is severe and apostolic: opposition to Paul's gospel is opposition by Satan, mediated through human agents who genuinely look like ministers. Discernment cannot rely on appearance. The *telos* — eschatological end — will expose what the disguise concealed (11:15). This passage stands behind every NT warning about wolves in sheep's clothing (Matt 7:15; Acts 20:29-30; 1 John 4:1)."
